{"title_page": "Safestyle UK", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Safestyle UK\n| type             = [[Public limited company]]\n| traded_as        = {{aim|SFE}}\n| parent           = Style Group UK\n| foundation       = 1992\n| location_city    = [[Bradford]]\n| location_country = [[England]]\n| key_people       = {{Unbulleted list|Mike Gallacher ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])|Giles Richell ([[Chief Operating Officer|COO]])|Rob Neale ([[Chief Financial Officer|CFO]])|[[Alan Lovell]] ([[Chairman]])}}\n| industry         = Glass, glazing and fenestration\n| products         = Replacement windows and doors\n| homepage         = [http://www.safestyle-windows.co.uk/ www.safestyle-windows.co.uk]\n}}\n\n'''Safestyle UK''' is part of the '''Style Group UK''' and is a provider of PVCu double glazed [[window]]s, [[door]]s, French doors, [[patio]] sliding doors and [[Conservatory (greenhouse)|conservatories]] in the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n==History==\nEstablished on 22 December 1992 with \u00a32,000,{{citation needed|date=December 2010}} in 2005 the company installed more than \u00a3100&nbsp;million of replacement windows and doors.{{citation needed|date=December 2010}} Safestyle\u2019s head office is in [[Bradford]], [[West Yorkshire]] and the company now has more than 40 branches across the [[United Kingdom]].\n\nIn 1996 the company expanded and set up a new division, Windowstyle, which manufactures Safestyle\u2019s double glazed [[Polyvinyl chloride#Unplasticized polyvinyl chloride .28uPVC.29|PVCu]] windows and doors in [[Barnsley]], [[South Yorkshire]]. The company has invested more than \u00a36.5&nbsp;million in Windowstyle to date, including \u00a32.5&nbsp;million worth of state-of-the-art glass toughening and processing machinery.{{citation needed|date=December 2010}} The facility is set in an {{convert|18|acre|m2|adj=on}} site, employs over 600 specialist production staff, runs 24 hours a day, 6 days a week, and produces more than 5,500 frames and 13,500 double glazed sealed units per week.{{citation needed|date=December 2010}} It is also the biggest employer in the area.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}\n\nIn 2005 the company was nominated in the national [http://www.g-awards.com/ G Awards], which take place annually and are open to all organisations in the glass, glazing and fenestration industries. Safestyle won the [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928045546/http://www.g-awards.com/gallery/05/ G05 Award] for Best Promotional Campaign of the Year, following that in 2006 with the [https://web.archive.org/web/20070420090040/http://www.g-awards.com/gallery/06/index.cfm G06 Award] for Best Customer Care.<ref name=\"auto\">[http://www.g-awards.com/awardinfo/winners.cfm The G-Awards Winners List] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217163714/http://www.g-awards.com/awardinfo/winners.cfm |date=17 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2006, Safestyle UK received Government-backed endorsement in the [[TrustMark]] scheme,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azobuild.com/news.aspx?newsID=1953|title=Trustmark Recognition for Safestyle UK|date=9 February 2006|website=AZoBuild.com}}</ref> a scheme also supported by the building industry and consumer groups. TrustMark-endorsed companies must have proven ability to make improvements and repairs inside and outside homes, adhering to high standards of workmanship and customer care.\n\nIn 2007, they have continued to win [https://web.archive.org/web/20080926122632/http://www.g-awards.com/gallery/07/ industry awards], winning the G07 Installer of the Year Award, and the G07 Health and Safety Initiative Award at the annual industry [http://www.g-awards.com/ G Awards].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nIn 2013, it was announced that Safestyle UK Ltd would be floated on the Alternative Investment Market in a deal worth \u00a370 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/10836388.Safestyle_UK_in___70_million_flotation_on_AIM/|title=Safestyle UK in \u00a370 million flotation on AIM|website=Bradford Telegraph and Argus}}</ref> The company began life in 1992 with \u00a32,000 of seed capital and was floated at \u00a31 a share, at which point co-founder Mitu Misra exited and used some of that money to write and produce his debut film, Lies We Tell, a northern noir set in Bradford and starring Gabriel Byrne and Harvey Keitel.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/feb/04/lies-we-tell-review|title=Lies We Tell review \u2013 culture clash in Bradford|last=Hans|first=Simran|date=4 February 2018|work=The Observer|accessdate=12 April 2019|issn=0029-7712}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 2003 the ''[[Sunday Mirror]]'' published a report on Safestyle UK's sales representatives' techniques, saying that \"it is almost a badge of honour to rip off a customer\".<ref>{{cite news | url= http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4161/is_20030615/ai_n12868202/ | accessdate=20 March 2008|title=Sunday Mirror investigates: sash and grab | work=Sunday Mirror | date=15 June 2003 | last=Evans | first=Dan}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2007 the [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]] upheld a complaint against a Safestyle advertisement which had been broadcast in September 2006.  They agreed that the advertisement had been misleading in two respects, both relating to the \"Buy now, pay next year\" credit terms.  The ASA ruled that the advertisement should not be shown again.<ref>{{cite web|author=Advertising Standards Authority |title=ASA Adjudications: Safestyle UK |url=http://www.asa.org.uk/asa/adjudications/Public/TF_ADJ_42290.htm |accessdate=20 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081122185823/http://www.asa.org.uk/asa/adjudications/Public/TF_ADJ_42290.htm |archivedate=22 November 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 the company was criticized by consumer rights charity [[Which?]] for its use of questionable sales techniques.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/local/localbrad/8234325.Watchdog_rap_for_window_company/|title=Watchdog rap for window company|website=Bradford Telegraph and Argus}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2011, Safestyle UK became the first company to be prosecuted under the [[Consumer Protection from Unfair Trading Regulations 2008]]. In an action<ref>[http://www.thisisscunthorpe.co.uk/news/Company-left-cold/article-3182713-detail/article.html \"Windows firm hit with \u00a322k bill after persistent cold-call visits\"] (4 February 2011)  ''This Is Scunthorpe'' {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110207020452/http://www.thisisscunthorpe.co.uk/news/Company-left-cold/article-3182713-detail/article.html |date=7 February 2011 }}</ref> brought by North Lincolnshire Council Trading Standards Department they were found guilty under paragraph 25 (ignoring a request not to return)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2008/1277/schedule/1/made|title=The Consumer Protection from Unfair Trading Regulations 2008|website=www.legislation.gov.uk}}</ref> and fined \u00a34,000 with \u00a318,000 costs for repeatedly calling on a consumer in [[Scunthorpe]].\n\n===Jeff Brown===\nJeff - a lifelong fan of Burnley F.C. - is also often the matchday host in the corporate lounge at Turf Moor. In 2013, Premier Range (the club's sponsor) challenged Jeff by offering to sponsor him \u00a310,000 to complete the new Jane Tomlinson Pennine Lancashire 10K.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.janetomlinsonappeal.com/media-and-gallery/news/2013/03/safestyle-jeffs-window-of-opportunity-to-support-good-cause/|title=Safestyle Jeff\u2019s window of opportunity to support good cause!|website=www.janetomlinsonappeal.com|accessdate=12 April 2019}}</ref> After the event, organisations in and around Burnley with charitable status were invited to make bids for a share of the cash pot to support one of their projects after the appeal decided to distribute the money to good causes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.janetomlinsonappeal.com/media-and-gallery/news/2014/06/janes-appeal-donates-%C2%A310000-to-good-causes-in-burnley/|title=Jane's Appeal donates \u00a310,000 to good causes in Burnley|website=www.janetomlinsonappeal.com|accessdate=12 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nJeff Brown, known for starring in Safestyle's window adverts since 1999, pleaded guilty in 2016 to six counts of being knowingly concerned in the fraudulent evasion of income tax and was given a 20 month prison sentence suspended for two years.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Macpherson|first1=Jon|title=Buy one, get one free advert man must pay \u00a353k - or face jail|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/you-buy-one-you-one-11865901|website=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=27 August 2017|date=9 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Robb|first1=Simon|title=TV advert double-glazing man convicted of \u00a358k tax evasion|url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/05/05/you-buy-one-you-get-one-free-double-glazing-man-convicted-of-tax-evasion-5860687/|website=Metro|accessdate=27 August 2017|date=5 May 2016}}</ref> Timothy Brennand, defending, said Brown has \u2018now got his finances in order\u2019 by employing an accountant and a book keeper.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/you-buy-one-you-one-11865901|title=Buy one, get one free advert man must pay \u00a353k - or face jail|last=Macpherson|first=Jon|date=9 September 2016|website=manchestereveningnews|accessdate=12 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Safestyle was fined \u00a3120,000 for \"aggressive sales\" by Sheffield Crown Court. Sheffield Crown Court was told that Safestyle UK employees used a variety of \"unlawful business practices\" to apply pressure to homeowners<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-44844422]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.safestyle-windows.co.uk Official Safestyle UK website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Safestyle Uk}}\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Bradford]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1992]]\n[[Category:Window manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Home improvement companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1992 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Alternative Investment Market]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Safestyle UK\n| type             = [[Public limited company]]\n| traded_as        = {{aim|SFE}}\n| parent           = Style Group UK\n| foundation       = 1992\n| location_city    = [[Bradford]]\n| location_country = [[England]]\n| key_people       = {{Unbulleted list|Mike Gallacher ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])|Giles Richell ([[Chief Operating Officer|COO]])|Rob Neale ([[Chief Financial Officer|CFO]])|[[Alan Lovell]] ([[Chairman]])}}\n| industry         = Glass, glazing and fenestration\n| products         = Replacement windows and doors\n| homepage         = [http://www.safestyle-windows.co.uk/ www.safestyle-windows.co.uk]\n}}\n\n'''Safestyle UK''' is part of the '''Style Group UK''' and is a provider of PVCu double glazed [[window]]s, [[door]]s, French doors, [[patio]] sliding doors and [[Conservatory (greenhouse)|conservatories]] in the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n==History==\nEstablished on 22 December 1992 with \u00a32,000,{{citation needed|date=December 2010}} in 2005 the company installed more than \u00a3100&nbsp;million of replacement windows and doors.{{citation needed|date=December 2010}} Safestyle\u2019s head office is in [[Bradford]], [[West Yorkshire]] and the company now has more than 40 branches across the [[United Kingdom]].\n\nIn 1996 the company expanded and set up a new division, Windowstyle, which manufactures Safestyle\u2019s double glazed [[Polyvinyl chloride#Unplasticized polyvinyl chloride .28uPVC.29|PVCu]] windows and doors in [[Barnsley]], [[South Yorkshire]]. The company has invested more than \u00a36.5&nbsp;million in Windowstyle to date, including \u00a32.5&nbsp;million worth of state-of-the-art glass toughening and processing machinery.{{citation needed|date=December 2010}} The facility is set in an {{convert|18|acre|m2|adj=on}} site, employs over 600 specialist production staff, runs 24 hours a day, 6 days a week, and produces more than 5,500 frames and 13,500 double glazed sealed units per week.{{citation needed|date=December 2010}} It is also the biggest employer in the area.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}\n\nIn 2005 the company was nominated in the national [http://www.g-awards.com/ G Awards], which take place annually and are open to all organisations in the glass, glazing and fenestration industries. Safestyle won the [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928045546/http://www.g-awards.com/gallery/05/ G05 Award] for Best Promotional Campaign of the Year, following that in 2006 with the [https://web.archive.org/web/20070420090040/http://www.g-awards.com/gallery/06/index.cfm G06 Award] for Best Customer Care.<ref name=\"auto\">[http://www.g-awards.com/awardinfo/winners.cfm The G-Awards Winners List] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217163714/http://www.g-awards.com/awardinfo/winners.cfm |date=17 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2006, Safestyle UK received Government-backed endorsement in the [[TrustMark]] scheme,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azobuild.com/news.aspx?newsID=1953|title=Trustmark Recognition for Safestyle UK|date=9 February 2006|website=AZoBuild.com}}</ref> a scheme also supported by the building industry and consumer groups. TrustMark-endorsed companies must have proven ability to make improvements and repairs inside and outside homes, adhering to high standards of workmanship and customer care.\n\nIn 2007, they have continued to win [https://web.archive.org/web/20080926122632/http://www.g-awards.com/gallery/07/ industry awards], winning the G07 Installer of the Year Award, and the G07 Health and Safety Initiative Award at the annual industry [http://www.g-awards.com/ G Awards].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nIn 2013, it was announced that Safestyle UK Ltd would be floated on the Alternative Investment Market in a deal worth \u00a370 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/10836388.Safestyle_UK_in___70_million_flotation_on_AIM/|title=Safestyle UK in \u00a370 million flotation on AIM|website=Bradford Telegraph and Argus}}</ref> The company began life in 1992 with \u00a32,000 of seed capital and was floated at \u00a31 a share, at which point co-founder Mitu Misra exited and used some of that money to write and produce his debut film, Lies We Tell, a northern noir set in Bradford and starring Gabriel Byrne and Harvey Keitel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/feb/04/lies-we-tell-review|title=Lies We Tell review \u2013 culture clash in Bradford|last=Hans|first=Simran|date=2018-02-04|work=The Observer|access-date=2019-04-12|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 2003 the ''[[Sunday Mirror]]'' published a report on Safestyle UK's sales representatives' techniques, saying that \"it is almost a badge of honour to rip off a customer\".<ref>{{cite news | url= http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4161/is_20030615/ai_n12868202/ | accessdate=20 March 2008|title=Sunday Mirror investigates: sash and grab | work=Sunday Mirror | date=15 June 2003 | last=Evans | first=Dan}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2007 the [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]] upheld a complaint against a Safestyle advertisement which had been broadcast in September 2006.  They agreed that the advertisement had been misleading in two respects, both relating to the \"Buy now, pay next year\" credit terms.  The ASA ruled that the advertisement should not be shown again.<ref>{{cite web|author=Advertising Standards Authority |title=ASA Adjudications: Safestyle UK |url=http://www.asa.org.uk/asa/adjudications/Public/TF_ADJ_42290.htm |access-date=20 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081122185823/http://www.asa.org.uk/asa/adjudications/Public/TF_ADJ_42290.htm |archive-date=22 November 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 the company was criticized by consumer rights charity [[Which?]] for its use of questionable sales techniques.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/local/localbrad/8234325.Watchdog_rap_for_window_company/|title=Watchdog rap for window company|website=Bradford Telegraph and Argus}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2011, Safestyle UK became the first company to be prosecuted under the [[Consumer Protection from Unfair Trading Regulations 2008]]. In an action<ref>[http://www.thisisscunthorpe.co.uk/news/Company-left-cold/article-3182713-detail/article.html \"Windows firm hit with \u00a322k bill after persistent cold-call visits\"] (4 February 2011)  ''This Is Scunthorpe'' {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110207020452/http://www.thisisscunthorpe.co.uk/news/Company-left-cold/article-3182713-detail/article.html |date=7 February 2011 }}</ref> brought by North Lincolnshire Council Trading Standards Department they were found guilty under paragraph 25 (ignoring a request not to return)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2008/1277/schedule/1/made|title=The Consumer Protection from Unfair Trading Regulations 2008|website=www.legislation.gov.uk}}</ref> and fined \u00a34,000 with \u00a318,000 costs for repeatedly calling on a consumer in [[Scunthorpe]].\n\n===Jeff Brown===\nJeff - a lifelong fan of Burnley F.C. - is also often the matchday host in the corporate lounge at Turf Moor. In 2013, Premier Range (the club's sponsor) challenged Jeff by offering to sponsor him \u00a310,000 to complete the new Jane Tomlinson Pennine Lancashire 10K.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.janetomlinsonappeal.com/media-and-gallery/news/2013/03/safestyle-jeffs-window-of-opportunity-to-support-good-cause/|title=Safestyle Jeff\u2019s window of opportunity to support good cause!|website=www.janetomlinsonappeal.com|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref> After the event, organisations in and around Burnley with charitable status were invited to make bids for a share of the cash pot to support one of their projects after the appeal decided to distribute the money to good causes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.janetomlinsonappeal.com/media-and-gallery/news/2014/06/janes-appeal-donates-%C2%A310000-to-good-causes-in-burnley/|title=Jane's Appeal donates \u00a310,000 to good causes in Burnley|website=www.janetomlinsonappeal.com|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>\n\nJeff Brown, known for starring in Safestyle's window adverts since 1999, pleaded guilty in 2016 to six counts of being knowingly concerned in the fraudulent evasion of income tax and was given a 20 month prison sentence suspended for two years.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Macpherson|first1=Jon|title=Buy one, get one free advert man must pay \u00a353k - or face jail|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/you-buy-one-you-one-11865901|website=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=27 August 2017|date=9 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Robb|first1=Simon|title=TV advert double-glazing man convicted of \u00a358k tax evasion|url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/05/05/you-buy-one-you-get-one-free-double-glazing-man-convicted-of-tax-evasion-5860687/|website=Metro|accessdate=27 August 2017|date=5 May 2016}}</ref> Timothy Brennand, defending, said Brown has \u2018now got his finances in order\u2019 by employing an accountant and a book keeper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/you-buy-one-you-one-11865901|title=Buy one, get one free advert man must pay \u00a353k - or face jail|last=Macpherson|first=Jon|date=2016-09-09|website=manchestereveningnews|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Safestyle was fined \u00a3120,000 for \"aggressive sales\" by Sheffield Crown Court. Sheffield Crown Court was told that Safestyle UK employees used a variety of \"unlawful business practices\" to apply pressure to homeowners<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-44844422]</ref>\n\n==References==\n<br />{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.safestyle-windows.co.uk Official Safestyle UK website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Safestyle Uk}}\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Bradford]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1992]]\n[[Category:Window manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Home improvement companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1992 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Alternative Investment Market]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Safestyle_UK"}
{"title_page": "123rd Illinois Infantry Regiment", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 123rd Illinois Volunteer Infantry Regiment\n| image= Flag of Illinois.svg\n| image_size = 200\n|caption=Illinois state flag\n|dates= September 6, 1862, to July 11, 1865\n|country= [[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[Infantry]], Mounted (1863-1864)\n|equipment= [[Spencer repeating rifle]]\n|battles= [[Battle of Perryville]]<br>[[Battle of Stones River]] (Murfreesboro II)<br>[[Battle of Vaught's Hill]]<br>[[Battle of Hoover's Gap]]<br>[[Battle of Chickamauga]]<br>[[Battle of Farmington, Tennessee|Battle of Farmington]]<br>[[Atlanta Campaign]]<br>[[Battle of Resaca]]<br>[[Battle of New Hope Church]]<br>[[Battle of Dallas]]<br>[[Battle of Marietta]]<br>[[Battle of Kennesaw Mountain]]<br>[[Kenner Garrard|Garrard's Raid]]<br>[[Wilson's Raid]]<br>[[Battle of Selma]]\n}}\nThe '''123rd Illinois Volunteer Infantry Regiment''' was an [[Infantry]] [[Regiment]] that served in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]]. In 1863 and 1864 it was temporarily known as the Mounted Infantry, 123rd Regiment as part of Wilder's Lightning Brigade.\n\n==Service==\nThis regiment was organized at Camp Terry, [[Mattoon, Illinois|Mattoon]], [[Coles County]], [[Illinois]], by Colonel James Monroe, who at the time was major of the [[7th Illinois Volunteer Regiment|7th Illinois Infantry]].<ref name=\"Reece\">Reece</ref> Companies A, C, D, H, I and K were from Coles County; B from [[Cumberland County, Illinois|Cumberland]]; E from [[Clark County, Illinois|Clark]]; F and G from Clark and [[Crawford County, Illinois|Crawford]]. As a colonel in 1861, [[Ulysses S. Grant]] organized his first command, the [[21st Illinois Volunteer Infantry Regiment]], in Mattoon.\n\nIt was mustered into service on September 6, 1862, with James Monroe as Colonel, Jonathan Biggs, of Westfield, Clark County, as Lieutenant Colonel, and James A. Connolly, of [[Charleston, Illinois]], as Major. On 19 September 1862, the Regiment was loaded into freight cars at Mattoon, and transported to [[Louisville, Kentucky]], where it was at once put to work, under Major General [[William \"Bull\" Nelson]], to fortify the city against Confederate General [[Braxton Bragg]], who was then advancing on it in pursuit of Union General [[Don Carlos Buell]].\n\nOn October 1, having been assigned to the Thirty-third Brigade (General [[William R. Terrill]]), Fourth Division (General [[James S. Jackson]]), in [[Alexander McDowell McCook|McCook's Corps]], the regiment started on the march under Buell, southward through Kentucky, after Bragg, who had turned back, and up to this time the regiment never had battalion drill, and hardly an attempt at company drill, as all the officers, except the colonel, were \"raw recruits\".\n\nJust 19 days after leaving Mattoon, the regiment engaged in the [[Battle of Perryville]], where 36 men were killed in action and 180 wounded.<ref name=\"Jared\">Jared </ref> Generals Terrill and Jackson were both killed immediately behind and within twenty feet of the line of the regiment. Among the wounded were Captain Coblentz of Company E, First Lieutenant S. M. Shepard of Company A and Adjutant Leander H. Hamlin. Following the devastating bloodshed the 123rd was assigned to protect the railroad bridge across the Green River at [[Munfordville]], [[Kentucky]], in November and December 1862. It has become known as the \"Battle for the Bridge,\" which began when the Union garrison led by [[John T. Wilder]], prior to his assuming command of the 123rd, surrendered during the [[Battle of Munfordville]].\n\nThe 123rd was initially assigned to the [[Army of the Ohio]] from September 1862 to November 1862, and then to the [[Army of the Cumberland]] from November 1862 to June 1865. The commanding general of the Army of the Cumberland was [[William Rosecrans]]. The regiment was in the 1st Brigade with Colonel Albert S. Hall, which was part of the 5th Division commanded by Brigadier General [[Joseph J. Reynolds]], reporting to Major General [[George Henry Thomas]]. \n\nIn February and March 1863, it was converted to mounted infantry. The 123rd Illinois' brigade became known as \"Wilder's [[Lightning Brigade (US Army of the Cumberland 1863)|Lightning Brigade]]\" commanded by [[John T. Wilder|Wilder]]. The brigade remained the 1st Brigade of the 5th Division, XIV Army Corps after its conversion. During this conversion, [[Spencer repeating rifle]]s, invented by [[Christopher Spencer]], were adopted as the command's primary weapon.<ref>[http://www.civilwar.si.edu/weapons_spencer.html A Spencer carbine at the Smithsonian Institution]</ref> The 123rd first used its new rifles in the [[Battle of Hoover's Gap]].<ref name=\"Repeaters\">Wilder's Lightning Brigade and Its Spencer Repeaters, Sunderland</ref>\n\n[[Image:Spencer-rifle transparent.png|thumb|left|300px|As part of the \"Wilder Lightning Brigade\" the 123rd was among the first units fighting in the Civil War to receive the [[Spencer repeating rifle]].]]\n\nThe new increase in firepower that the Spencer gave, allowed the 123rd and its brigade mates to maul numerically superior Confederate infantry and cavalry in several engagements. The regiment served quite well through the remainder of the [[Tullahoma campaign|Tullahoma Campaign]] and as part of the Lightning Brigade, was one of the few positive notes in the calamitous [[Chickamauga Campaign]]. \n\nDuring the [[Siege of Chattanooga]], the Lightning Brigade disbanded, and four of its regiments shifted to the Cavalry Corps where they served for the remainder of the war. The 123rd and the 72nd Indiana were sent to the 3rd Brigade of the 2nd Division.\n\nDuring the [[Battle of Selma]], First Lieutenant O. J. McManus, Sergeants J. S. Mullen and Henry E. Cross, Corporal McMurry and Privates Daniel Cook, John Bowman, Marion White and Henry Woodruff were killed, with 50 wounded, including Lieutenant Colonel Biggs, Adjutant L. B. Bane, Captains W. E. Adams and Owen Wiley, Lieutenants Alex. McNutt and J. R. Harding.\n\nLate in the war, the regiment pursued Confederate General [[John Bell Hood]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.16thconfederatecavalry.com/timelinebattles/rome.html |title=Battle Near Rome, Georgia, October 12, 1864 |access-date=2018-11-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707060209/http://www.16thconfederatecavalry.com/timelinebattles/rome.html |archive-date=2011-07-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The unit was instrumental in the capture of former Confederate capital [[Montgomery, Alabama]].\n\nIn June 1865 new recruits and some veterans were transferred to the [[61st Illinois Volunteer Infantry Regiment|61st Regiment]] as the 123rd prepared to disband.<ref name=\"ILNG\">GlobalSecurity.org 1st Battalion, 123d Infantry</ref> Those who remained were mustered out June 27, 1865, by Captain L. M. Hosea and formally discharged at [[Springfield, Illinois]], on July 11, 1865.\n\n==Total strength and casualties==\nThe regiment lost during service three officers and 82 enlisted men killed and mortally wounded and one officer and 133 enlisted men by disease for a total of 219.<ref name=\"OoB\">Official Records of the American Civil War of the Union and Confederate Armies, U.S. War Department</ref>\n\n==Commanders==\nColonel James Monroe: September 6, 1862 - October 7, 1863 (killed at the Battle of Farmington)<br>\nBrigadier General of Volunteers [[James S. Jackson]]: October 1, 1862 - October 8, 1862 (killed at the Battle of Perryville)<br>\nBrigadier General of Volunteers [[William R. Terrill]]: September 9, 1862 - October 8, 1862 (killed at the Battle of Perryville)<br>\nLt. Colonel [[James A. Connolly]]<br>\nCaptain Oscar R. Bane<br>\nColonel [[John T. Wilder]]: May 6, 1863 - November 1864 (resignation)<br>\nBrigadier General [[Kenner Garrard]]: May 20, 1864 - October 28, 1864<br>\nMajor General [[James H. Wilson]]: October 28, 1864 - June 27, 1865\n\n==Officers==\n*Surgeon John Milton Phipps, July 2, 1863 - March 30, 1864.\n*[[Sergeant]] [[John Hamilton Morgan]]<ref>[http://theancestorfiles.blogspot.com/2009/02/morgan-4-john-morgan-funeral-address.html John Morgan Funeral Address]</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.worldcat.org/title/blue-lightning-wilders-mounted-infantry-brigade-in-the-battle-of-chickamauga/oclc/232639520?loc=02333\n| title       = Blue Lightning: Wilder's Mounted Brigade in the Battle of Chickamauga\n| author      = Baumgartner, Richard A.\n| publisher   = Blue Acorn Press\n| location    = Huntington WV\n| year        = 2007\n| isbn        = 978-1-885033-35-2\n| asin        = \n| oclc        = \n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.worldcat.org/title/three-years-in-the-army-of-the-cumberland-the-letters-and-diary-of-major-james-a-connolly/oclc/906602437&referer=brief_results\n| title       = Three Years in the Army of the Cumberland: The Letters and Diary of Major James A. Connolly\n| author      = Connolly, James A.\n| editor      = Paul M. Angle\n| publisher   = Indiana University Press\n| location    = Bloomington, IN\n| year        = 1959\n| isbn        = 9780527190002\n| asin        = \n| oclc        = 906602437\n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.battlefields.org/learn/primary-sources/battle-hoovers-gap\n| title       = Primary Sources: The Road to Chickamauga\n| author      = Connolly, James A\n| publisher   = American Battlefield Trust\n| location    = Washington, DC\n| year        = \n| isbn        = \n| asin        = \n| oclc        = \n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.worldcat.org/title/autumn-of-glory-the-army-of-tennessee-1862-1865/oclc/1147753151?referer=di&ht=edition\n| title       = Autumn of Glory: The Army of Tennessee 1862\u20131865\n| author      = Connelly, Thomas L\n| publisher